[31mThis is really helpful — now I can see the exact rejection details. Let me break down what Apple is actually asking for:[39m
[31m[39m
[31mIssue 1 (2.1.0) — CONFIRMED: Subscriptions not submitted with the app. Apple says it explicitly: "one or more of the in-app purchase products have not been submitted for review." You need to attach them to the version and upload a new binary.[39m
[31m[39m
[31mIssue 2 (3.1.2) — It's about the Terms of Use (EULA), not the paywall UI. Apple wants a functional link to your Terms of Use either in your App Store description or as a custom EULA in App Store Connect. Your privacy policy link is probably set, but you need to add the Terms link.[39m
[31m[39m
[31mIssue 3 (5.1.1) — Camera purpose string is too vague. They want a more descriptive NSCameraUsageDescription that explains specifically why and how you use the camera (for OCR recipe scanning).[39m
[31m[39m
[31mSo here's your action plan:[39m
[31m[39m
[31mFor Issue 1: You need to submit a new binary that includes the subscriptions. Since the IAP section isn't appearing on your version page, you'll likely need to upload a new build (bump your build number to 4), and when you create the new submission, the subscription selector should appear. This is a known quirk with rejected builds.[39m
[31m[39m
[31mFor Issue 2: Two options — go to App Information in the left sidebar and look for a License Agreement (EULA) section where you can either add a custom EULA or link to yours. Or add your Terms URL to your App Store description text.[39m
[31m[39m
[31mFor Issue 3: What does your current camera permission string say? Paste your app.json or app.config.js so I can write you a proper one.[39m
[31m[39m
