[90mThere's your problem — there's no camera permission string at all in your config. Apple saw a camera request with no NSCameraUsageDescription or a default/generic one from a plugin.[39m
[90m[39m
[90mAdd this to your ios section in app.json:[39m
[90m[39m
[90mjson[39m
[90m"ios": {[39m
[90m  "supportsTablet": false,[39m
[90m  "bundleIdentifier": "com.alstiginc.chefscale",[39m
[90m  "infoPlist": {[39m
[90m    "NSCameraUsageDescription": "ChefScale uses your camera to scan and photograph recipes, ingredient lists, and nutrition labels so you can quickly import them into the app for scaling and cost tracking."[39m
[90m  }[39m
[90m}[39m
[90mThat's specific, explains the purpose, and gives concrete examples — exactly what Apple wants.[39m
[90m[39m
[90mNow — are you using expo-camera or expo-image-picker for the OCR scanning? If you're using expo-image-picker, you'll also need:[39m
[90m[39m
[90mjson[39m
[90m"NSPhotoLibraryUsageDescription": "ChefScale accesses your photo library so you can import photos of recipes, ingredient lists, and nutrition labels for scanning and recipe entry."[39m
[90mAdd both to be safe. Then rebuild (bump build number to 4) and upload.[39m
[90m[39m
[90mThat handles Issue 3. Ready to tackle Issue 2 (the EULA/Terms link)? That one is an App Store Connect fix, no code needed.[39m
